{{Infobox Roman emperor |name =Regalianus |full name = P. C. Regalianus<ref name=Jones762 /> |title = [[Roman usurper|Usurper]] of the [[Roman Empire]] |image= Antoninianus-Dryantilla-RIC 0002.jpg |caption =[[Antoninianus]] issued by Regilianus' wife, Sulpicia Dryantilla, who is shown here as ''[[Augusta (honorific)|Augusta]]''.<ref>All the coinage of Regalianus and Dryantilla is composed of [[antoninianus|antoniniani]] struck over other coins, mostly from the reign of [[Septimius Severus]], [[Alexander Severus]] and [[Maximinus Thrax]]. The only mint to issue coins for Regalianus was the mint of [[Carnuntum]] in [[Pannonia]] (modern [[Austria]]); most of the coins have been found in a small zone around the same city, testifying for a little spread of the rebellion.</ref> |reign =''c.'' 260 |predecessor =[[Gallienus]] |successor =[[Gallienus]] |spouse 1 =[[Sulpicia Dryantilla]] (senatorial descent) |spouse 2 = |issue = |dynasty = |father = |mother = |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date =260 |death_place =[[Carnuntum]], [[Pannonia]] |place of burial = |}} {{Campaignbox Crisis of the Third Century}}
'''P. C(assius?) Regalianus''' (died 260) was a [[Dacia|Dacian]] general<ref name=Akerman>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=z-NCAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA80&dq=Regalianus#v=onepage&q=Regalianus&f=false|title=A descriptive catalogue of rare and unedited Roman coins:from the earliest period of the Roman coinage, to the extinction of the empire under Constantinus Paleologos|first=John Yonge |last=Akerman|page=80}}</ref> who turned against the [[Roman Empire]] and became himself emperor for a brief period, being murdered by the hands who raised him to power.<ref name=Akerman />
==Career== The main source of information is the unreliable ''[[Historia Augusta]]''. Other sources are [[Eutropius (historian)|Eutropius]], who calls him [[Trebellianus]], and [[Aurelius Victor]] and the ''[[Epitome]]''{{which|date=April 2014}}, which call him Regillianus. About his origin, the ''[[Thirty Tyrants (Roman)|Tyranni Triginta]]'' says he was a [[Dacia]]n, a kinsman of [[Decebalus]].<ref>''Historia Augusta'', Tyranni Triginta, 10:8</ref> He probably was of senatorial rank, and had received military promotion from the Emperor [[Valerian (emperor)|Valerian]].<ref name=Jones762>Jones, p. 762</ref>
After the defeat and capture of Valerian in the east (260), the border populations felt insecure, and elected their own emperors to guarantee they would have leaders against the foreign threats.<ref name=Leadbetter>{{cite web |last=Leadbetter |first=William |url=http://www.roman-emperors.org/ingen.htm |title=Regalianus (260 A.D.) |work=De Imperatoribus Romanis |year=1998}}</ref> The population and the army of the province of [[Pannonia]] had chosen [[Ingenuus]], and elected him emperor, but the lawful emperor, Gallienus, had defeated the usurper.<ref>Jones, p. 457</ref>
Gallienus had moved to [[Italia (Roman province)|Italia]], however, to deal with an invasion of the [[Alamanni]]. The local population, facing the threat of the [[Sarmatian]]s, elected Regalianus emperor,<ref>Canduci, p. 85</ref> who raised his wife, [[Sulpicia Dryantilla]], who was of noble lineage, to the rank of ''[[Augusta (honorific)|Augusta]]'' to strengthen his position.<ref name=Leadbetter /> Regalianus bravely fought thereafter against the Sarmatians. Short time after his victory, he was killed by a coalition of his own people and of the [[Roxolani]].<ref name=Leadbetter />
A few anecdotes survive about this man, in the brief biographical sketch of him given in the Book on [[Thirty Tyrants (Roman)|Thirty Tyrants]] in the ''[[Historia Augusta]]'': it is stated for example that he was raised to the throne because of his name (Regalianus, "of a king" or "kingly"); when his soldiers heard this jest they greeted Regalianus as their emperor.<ref>''Historia Augusta'', Tyranni Triginta, 10:6</ref>
